>>128743119
If Clears are under 1000 AUD that's like £570 GBP, that's a huge deal really. It's cheaper than most of the mid-Focal models in the UK like Elear etc. Even if the headband was a meh that's insane value 2bh

My clears have held up pretty well but they've not had as much use as my aryas.. my aryas definitely feel cheaper made, the leather on the pads began to peel off and the rails are splitting somehow, maybe tightened too much, not sure how the construction is done. However can't beat that tall and wide sound that only the Arya seems to give.
Ironically the Sundaras feel way better built at £300 as they have metallic casings. But Sundaras are incredible value for mid-range headphones. HifiMan definitely used to be known for QC issues but they've changed their ways in the last 3-4 years or so. I heard lots of complaints pre-Sundara release but after then they seem to have orientated themselves into a proper high end company for audio stuff.

In terms of source I don't venture beyond headphones too much when it comes to money, audiophile circles are full of snake oil and people insisting they can hear things better but it's not really true. So basically I just use Qobuz most of the time as a music source, if I even listen to it. Weirdly I can go months without listening to music,I just generally enjoy hearing audio a lot better in ambience, games, etc. The Arya's soundstage can really enhance RPGs in that respect sometimes. In terms of DAC/AMP I have to confess I mostly use my sound card (it is a top end one though) which has both integrated. It's just way more convenient and I hear very little difference 2bh

A powerplay is a general term used in cricket to describe a set number of overs during a limited-overs match (like ODI and T20) with specific fielding restrictions, while the BBL power surge is a specific variation of a powerplay that is used in the BBL competition. The powerplay rule is different for ODI and T20 and BBL, but essentially it limits the number of fielders in the outfield for a set number of overs. It can help the batting side hit more boundaries, but it can conversely work against a batting side since more fielders in the infield means singles are almost impossible. It's supposed to make the match more exciting and adds an extra layer of strategy and tactics to the match since captains have to think about at what time the powerplay/power surge is best utilised, what bowlers should bowl those powerplay/power surge overs, etc.

Inter director Beppe Marotta refuses to comment on the recent Juventus scandal and rules out a return to the club, revealing that one of the leading Italian politicians, supporting Southampton, has been trolling him because of Carlos Alcaraz.

The Nerazzurri CEO released an interview with Il Corriere della Sera and was asked his thoughts on the chaos surrounding his ex-club Juventus, who have been docked 15 points for financial irregularities.

“I won’t discuss the work others did, I think about the present with the Nerazzurri. My years at Juventus are part of the past and I can only have great memories,” he said.

Asked whether he would return to the club, as a few reports have recently suggested, he replied: “I am happy with the path I’ve taken. I feel well at Inter and I am focused on contributing to more victories.”

The 65-year-old spent eight years at Juventus, winning, among other things, seven Serie A titles.

During his interview with Corriere della Sera, Marotta also spoke about his ambition of someday quitting his football career and entering politics.

“I was asked to do so, but everyone has a dream and mine is to enter as a technician and not affiliated with any political party,” he said.

From 1872-1876 the only national teams were England and Scotland, so naturally their annual match was the world championship match. Of these 4 matches, Scotland won 1, England won 1, and they both drew twice. Naturally, each team received a star from both of these world cups. From 1876, the Wales national team also played, and from 1882, Ireland also played internationals. It's difficult to determine who was the world champion during these years, so no world cups were awarded.

In 1884 the British Home Championship was established; an annual tournament between 100% of the world's national football teams. The first non-British Isles international match was in 1902, so from 1884 to 1902, this tournament determined the world champion. Scotland won 11 and England won 10. In 1966, England won the FIFA World cup, so Scotland and England both have 12 stars.

In addition, Great Britain won the Gold in football at the Olympics in 1900, 1908, and 1912. As per Uruguayan science, these pre-World Cup Olympic golds count as world championships, therefore world cups, so that's 3 extra stars for both Scotland and England.

Per these findings could you please respectfully kneel for the two teams that are tied for the most successful national teams in history: Scotland and England both tied at 15 world cups each.

>>128748969
>Oh wow I would think the opposite
It's a bit of both really. Women don't serve as well, so there are more rallies and therefore more chances for things to go either way because rallies tend to go 50/50. OTOH, very good servers tend to pull ahead significantly since they can get into rallies frequently on their opponent's serve while staying relatively safe on their own serve. Think the two finalists today, the Williams, Osaka or Barty. Barty's not exactly as strong in the rallies as Swiatek (especially not with her poor backhand), but she had the best serve numbers on tour so that was more than enough to compensate.

In other words, it's not like the men's tour where having a shit serve would make it near impossible to be competitive unless you return like Schwartzman, but having an elite serve is a huge boost. To give you an idea, righty Pliskova has the worst return points won percentage in the top 100, but she still wins 40% of a return points. 40% return points won on the ATP would put you amongst the best returners in the game. OTOH, while her serve is good, if she had a serve points won percentage even like Nadal who's not terrible but not amazing on serve either, she'd do the grand slam every year. Instead, she's top 5 material on her best days.

>>128749078
I'll try to make it shorter:
Women have more rallies than men, and rallies tend towards being 50/50 in terms of results (unless you're vastly superior at rallying like a Swiatek kind of player). Having a huge serve saves you from the uncertainty of rallies, so big servers tend to do well and you see them often at the top of the game. But the coin has two faces: because women have more rallies, not having a good serve isn't going to get you shitcanned like on the men's tour because it's also unlikely that your opponent also can serve very well.

>>128692927
If you want to give it a go

ffmpeg -y -i *.mp4 -t 16 -vf scale=1280:-1 -c:v libvpx-vp9 -row-mt 1 -b:v 2M -an -pass 1 -f webm /dev/null && ffmpeg -i *.mp4 -t 16 -vf scale=1280:-1 -c:v libvpx-vp9 -row-mt 1 -b:v 2M -an -pass 2 Output.webm

-t ** = How long you want the video to last
-b:v *M = 32/t gives you the max bitrate you can use to stay under the new 4M webm limit

And it's done twice to get the two-pass encode

posts.com:
The following can literally turn any of you into goat material if you learn it.

Allnof fighting, be ot striking or wrestling revolves around the next 4 core concepts: rhythm, distance, balance and pace.
All fighters at all levels look to stablish these aspects over the other and read the opponent through these
If you have broken rhythm (changes in speed, punch out put, how and where you land x punch) the opponent cannot read your rhythm wich means he can't begin to set up anything and if you can't read your opponent rhythm for whatever reason you can force them to create a certain rhythm by intentionally doing a specific move when they do a specific move so they think they catched a rhythm and you begin attacking.
Distance is obvious, hit and not get hit and it builds from rhythm but to disrupt someone sense of distance you can intentionally get your head or your feet closer without moving the other wich will make someone think you are closer or further than they think, if you can't catch the distance, standing still will make the opponent initiate the attack and you can get a better sense of distance than of you are following them.
Balance is how they stand to throw any technique, changes in distance can throw someone out of balance because they have to reset.
This is where things like feints, volume, heavy punches, counters enter, there are various individual methods to deal with each but having better balance already beats them all.
Pacing is not just who attacks first, if you are resting you can expect the opponent to be more active amd viceversa.

Thing like timing come from reading some rhythm, having the distance down and shooting when needed but if you control these aspects no one can read you and you can.
Try these with a single technique and you will see massive improvement instantly.

posts.com:
Touch of death
This needs three things, fast twitch muscle fibers, high levels of rate of force development and body mechanics.

If you develop your strength with isometric holds, slow reps and slow negatives this preps your muscles to absorb and produce high amounts of force.
Then do power exercises with an explosive form (slow eccentric fast concentric or oly lifts.
Then do explosive exercises where you are doing fast exercises like med ball slams, sprints, box jumps, stuff like that.
Finally plyometrics start with slow stretch plyos and then move to fast stretch plyos.
Rate of force development is trained by doing exercises where there is a balance of strength and speed, for example sledge pushed, up hill sprints, fast reps and this allows to produce as much force as possible at a faster rate.
Then body mechanics, leg drive, weight shifting, hip rotation, elastic recoil all add a shit ton of power to your punches.

Infinite cardio
Aerobic capacity is what lets you move for long periods of time and anaerobic capacity is the gas tank for explosive stuff.

First do a high intensity pace that you can sustain for 5 minutes, it can be anything but for example aim to run a 5 minute mile. To do that do 4 400m sprints at 75 seconds wich equals a 5 minute mile, then run 1 mile at whatever pace you can handle and over time reduce the time, doing both eventually gets you a 5 minute mile.
Do interval sprints during jogs, you can pick any exercise but alternate the intensity between max effort and moderate effort.
Then do max effort cardio, again any exercise works but for example do sprints.
Lastly do uphill jogs for long distances, this doesn't have an alternative.
Doing all these 4 build both energy systems and you will be able to high a very high intensity pace and be able to maintain that pace.

That's all for tonight.

Brady is an enigma. He has low talent but hes clearly the GOAT. Hes regarded as clutch, but by dumb statistical analysis hes definitely a worse, less efficient, less productive QB in postseason than in the regular season. In all his Super Bowls but one, he played mediocrely—his best performance by a wide margin was the one he lost to the Eagles in the 19-20 season. Some stats-obsessed bugmen have stridently made this sort of case against Brady but eventually gave in to the fact that conventional, empirical analysis breaks down here. He just wins. The "Brady is a b-tier talent who just worked harder than everyone else" meme is bullshit. Brady is physically gifted, just not with speed. But he's always had a fucking cannon which for some reason people never seem to want to acknowledge. Just this year he threw a ball like 60-70 yards in the air and that's in his mid-40's. And he has the hand-eye coordination necessary to throw with accuracy as well as strength. He has unusually good balance, peripheral vision and dexterity which lets him move around so well in the pocket while keeping his eyes downfield. He's an extreme outlier in terms of durability. The dude has played forever and almost never misses time due to injury. He's tall so he can see over the line, and he has long arms and large hands which helped his qb sneak become basically automatic and minimize fumbles. He has literally every physical trait you look for in a qb besides the ability to run.

And that's just the physical component. mentally, he's exactly what you want as well. He's incredibly smart, processes things quickly, almost always, makes the smart decision, is competitive as hell, is a cold-blooded killer in clutch moments and he's not a diva or a sperg. His only real flaw psychologically is that he's a sore loser but he mitigates that by just not losing very often.

There's nothing odd about Brady's success. The only reason he was so unheralded going into the draft was because of the league's obsession with abs and 40 times which have always had fuck-all to do with playing quarterback. And they're still falling for it today. Teams are talking themselves into Kyler Murray, Justin Fields, Trey Lance, et al all because muh athleticism. A guy like Purdy only gets to start by accident. But when he does it's like "oh, right, throwing the ball is still the thing that works." qb athleticism is the dumbest thing to obsess over
